<section xml:id="section-more-on-complex-solutions-to-quadratic-equations">

    <title>More on Complex Solutions to Quadratic Equations</title>

    <introduction>
        <p>When we solve a quadratic equation, sometimes there are no real solutions. In this section we will explore when that happens and what it means on a graph. We will also learn how to handle complex solutions algebraically.</p>
        <figure>
            <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
            <sbsgroup>
                <sidebyside>
                    <video youtube="zb-PYxwjGrg" />
                </sidebyside>
                <sidebyside>
                    <video youtube="11EwTcRMPn8" />
                </sidebyside>
            </sbsgroup>
        </figure>
    </introduction>

    <subsection>
        <title>Applications with Real or Complex Solutions</title>

        <p>Let's look at an application where we will determine whether the solutions are real or complex. In a stunt plane performance, a pilot plans to dive the plane toward the ground and then back up. The plane's height can be modeled by a quadratic function. If one possible function is <m>h</m>, where <m>h(t)=\frac{1}{2}t^2-5t+12</m>, with <m>t</m> standing for time in seconds after the stunt begins, determine whether the plane would hit the ground during the stunt.</p>

        <p>To check whether the plane on that flight path would hit the ground, we will solve the equation <m>h(t)=0</m>. We will solve this equation with <xref ref="fact-the-quadratic-formula" text="title">the quadratic formula</xref>. First, we identify that <m>a=\substitute{\frac{1}{2}}</m>, <m>b=\substitute{-5}</m> and <m>c=\substitute{12}</m>.</p>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" valign="middle">
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>t\amp=\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{-(\substitute{-5})\pm\sqrt{(\substitute{-5})^2-4(\substitute{\sfrac{1}{2}})(\substitute{12})}}{2(\substitute{\sfrac{1}{2}})}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{5\pm\sqrt{25-24}}{1}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=5\pm\sqrt{1}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=5\pm1</mrow>
                </md>
                So, either:
                <md>
                    <mrow>t=6\amp\amp\text{ or }\amp\amp t=4</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <figure>
                <caption>Graph of <m>y=h(t)</m></caption>
                <image>
                    <description></description>
                    <latex-image >
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[ymin=-1,ymax=3,xmin=-1,xmax=8,
                                ytick={0,1,...,2},
                                minor ytick={-1,-0.5,...,2.5},
                                xtick={1,2,...,7},
                                minor xtick={1,2,...,8},
                                xlabel={$t$ seconds},ylabel={$y$ feet}]
                            \addplot+[domain=2.354:7.646, samples=200] {0.5*x^2-5*x+12} node[pos=0.5,below] {$y=h(t)$};
                            \addplot [soliddot,color=secondcolor] coordinates {(4,0) (6,0)};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                    </latex-image >
                </image>
            </figure>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>This equation has two real solutions and we can see from the graph that the real solutions are the zeros of <m>h</m>. The solution <m>4</m> shows that the plane would hit the ground <m>4</m> seconds into the stunt.</p>

        <p>To avoid hitting the ground, the pilot adjusted the function to <m>p</m>, where <m>p(t)=\frac{1}{2}t^2-5t+12.5</m>. To see whether the plane on this flight path would hit the ground, we will solve the equation <m>p(t)=0</m>. We will again use the quadratic formula to solve this equation. We identify that <m>a=\substitute{\frac{1}{2}}</m>, <m>b=\substitute{-5}</m> and <m>c=\substitute{12.5}</m>.</p>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" valign="middle">
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>t\amp=\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{-(\substitute{-5})\pm\sqrt{(\substitute{-5})^2-4(\substitute{\sfrac{1}{2}})(\substitute{12.5})}}{2(\substitute{\sfrac{1}{2}})}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{5\pm\sqrt{25-25}}{1}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=5\pm\sqrt{0}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=5\pm0</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=5</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <figure>
                <caption>Graph of <m>y=p(t)</m></caption>
                <image>
                    <description></description>
                    <latex-image >
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[ymin=-1,ymax=3,xmin=-1,xmax=8,
                                ytick={0,1,...,2},
                                minor ytick={-1,-0.5,...,2.5},
                                xtick={1,2,...,7},
                                minor xtick={1,2,...,8},
                                xlabel={$t$ seconds},ylabel={$y$ feet}]
                            \addplot+[domain=2.551:7.449, samples=200] {0.5*x^2-5*x+12.5} node[pos=0.4,left] {$y=p(t)$};
                            \addplot [soliddot,color=secondcolor] coordinates {(5,0)};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                    ]]>
                    </latex-image >
                </image>
            </figure>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>This equation has one real solution because <m>p</m> has one zero. This time the plane would hit the ground <m>5</m> seconds into the stunt.</p>

        <p>The pilot again adjusted the flight path to <m>q</m>, where <m>q(t)=\frac{1}{2}t^2-5t+13</m>. We will solve the equation <m>q(t)=0</m> using the quadratic formula. Identify that <m>a=\substitute{\frac{1}{2}}</m>, <m>b=\substitute{-5}</m> and <m>c=\substitute{13}</m>.</p>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" valign="middle">
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>t\amp=\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{-(\substitute{-5})\pm\sqrt{(\substitute{-5})^2-4(\substitute{\sfrac{1}{2}})(\substitute{13})}}{2(\substitute{\sfrac{1}{2}})}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{5\pm\sqrt{25-26}}{1}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=5\pm\sqrt{-1}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <figure>
                <caption>Graph of <m>y=q(t)</m></caption>
                <image>
                    <description></description>
                    <latex-image>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[ymin=-1,ymax=3,xmin=-1,xmax=8,
                                ytick={0,1,...,2},
                                minor ytick={-1,-0.5,...,2.5},
                                xtick={1,2,...,7},
                                minor xtick={1,2,...,8},
                                xlabel={$t$ seconds},ylabel={$y$ feet}]
                            \addplot+[domain=2.764:7.236, samples=200] {0.5*x^2-5*x+13} node[pos=0.4,left] {$y=q(t)$};
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                ]]>
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </sidebyside>

        <p>Because the radicand is negative, there are no real solutions and the function has no horizontal intercepts. This means the plane will not touch the ground.</p>

        <p>In general, the radicand of the quadratic formula, <m>b^2-4ac</m> is called the <term>discriminant</term><idx><h>discriminant</h></idx>. The sign of the discriminant will tell us how many horizontal intercepts a quadratic function will have
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>When a quadratic function <m>h</m> has two horizontal intercepts, the equation <m>h(t)=0</m> has two real solutions.  The discriminant will be a positive number so that the <m>\pm</m> from the quadratic formula will provide two solutions.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>When a quadratic function <m>p</m> has one horizontal intercept, the equation <m>p(t)=0</m> has one real solution. The discriminant will be zero so that the <m>\pm</m> from the quadratic formula will provide only one solution.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>When a quadratic function <m>q</m> has no horizontal intercepts, the equation <m>q(t)=0</m> has no real solutions, but it has two complex solutions. The discriminant will be a negative number so that the <m>\sqrt{\phantom{\Delta}}</m> from the quadratic formula will provide imaginary numbers, and then the <m>\pm</m> will provide two complex solutions.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p><url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Futsal">Futsal</url><fn><url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Futsal">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Futsal</url></fn> is a form of what is usually called soccer in the United States. The game is played on a hard court surface and is usually indoors. The ceiling is out of bounds, so if the ball hits the ceiling it goes to the opposing team.</p>

                <p>If a player kicks the ball from the ground with an upward velocity of <m>8</m> meters per second, the ball's height in meters can be modeled by the quadratic function <m>h</m>, where <m>h(t)=-4.9t^2+8t</m>, with <m>t</m> standing for time in seconds after the ball was kicked. If the ceiling height is <m>4</m> meters, the minimum height allowed by regulation, determine whether the ball will hit the ceiling.</p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p>To see whether the ball will hit the ceiling, we will solve the equation <m>h(t)=4</m>. We could complete the square or use the quadratic formula. Because this equation has decimal coefficients we will use the quadratic formula. We put the equation in standard form and identify that <m>a=\substitute{-4.9}</m>, <m>b=\substitute{8}</m> and <m>c=\substitute{-4}</m>.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>-4.9t^2+8t\amp=4</mrow>
                        <mrow>-4.9t^2+8t-4\amp=0</mrow>
                        <mrow>t\amp=\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{-\substitute{8}\pm\sqrt{\substitute{8}^2-4(\substitute{-4.9})(\substitute{-4})}}{2(\substitute{-4.9})}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{-8\pm\sqrt{64-78.4}}{-9.8}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{-8\pm\sqrt{-14.4}}{-9.8}</mrow>
                    </md>
                The radicand is negative so we can conclude that there are no real solutions to the equation <m>h(t)=4</m>. That means the parabola will not cross the line <m>y=4</m> and the ball will not hit the ceiling.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <!-- TODO: this one can be interactive -->
            <statement>
                <p>If a player kicks the ball from the ground with an upward velocity of <m>10</m> meters per second, the ball's height in meters can be modeled by the quadratic function <m>h</m>, where <m>h(t)=-4.9t^2+10t</m>, with <m>t</m> standing for time in seconds after the ball was kicked. If the ceiling height is <m>4.5</m> meters, determine whether the ball will hit the ceiling.</p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p>To see whether the ball will hit the ceiling, we will solve the equation <m>h(t)=4.5</m>. We will use the quadratic formula because this equation has decimal coefficients. We put the equation in standard form and identify that <m>a=\substitute{-4.9}</m>, <m>b=\substitute{10}</m> and <m>c=\substitute{-4.5}</m>.</p>

                <p><md>
                <mrow>-4.9t^2+10t\amp=4.5</mrow>
                <mrow>-4.9t^2+10t-4.5\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>t\amp=\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=\frac{-\substitute{10}\pm\sqrt{\substitute{10}^2-4(\substitute{-4.9})(\substitute{-4.5})}}{2(\substitute{-4.9})}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=\frac{-10\pm\sqrt{100-88.2}}{-9.8}</mrow>
                <mrow>\amp=\frac{-10\pm\sqrt{11.8}}{-9.8}</mrow>
                </md>The radicand is positive so there are two real solutions to the equation <m>h(t)=4.5</m>. That means the parabola will cross the line <m>y=4.5</m> and the ball will hit the ceiling.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Solving Equations with Complex Solutions</title>

        <p>In a physical context we may only want to know whether solutions are real or complex. Or we may want to find the solutions. When the radicand is negative, we need to go into the complex number system. First we will revisit the definition of complex numbers. Recall that <m>i</m> is defined as <m>\sqrt{-1}</m>.</p>

<!-- TODO: The definition is copied from 65. Do we want to repeat it for the printed book or use a cross-reference? -->
        <definition>
            <title>Complex Number</title>
            <idx><h>complex number</h></idx>
            <statement>
                <p>A <url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number"><term>complex number</term></url><fn><url href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex<underscore />number</url></fn><idx><h>complex number</h></idx> is a number that can be expressed in the form <m>a + bi</m><idx><h sortby="a"><m>a + bi</m> form</h></idx>, where <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are real numbers and <m>i</m> is the imaginary unit. In this expression, <m>a</m> is the <term>real part</term><idx><h>complex number</h><h>real part</h></idx> and <m>b</m> (not <m>bi</m>) is the <term>imaginary part</term><idx><h>complex number</h><h>imaginary part</h></idx>.</p>
            </statement>
        </definition>

        <p>Here are some examples of solving equations that have complex solutions.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve for <m>s</m> in <m>s^2-10s=-34</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We will use the method of completing the square. To do so, we need to add <m>\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^2=(-5)^2=25</m> to both sides to complete the square.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>s^2-10s\amp=-34</mrow>
                        <mrow>s^2-10s\addright{25}\amp=-34\addright{25}</mrow>
                        <mrow>(s-5)^2\amp=-9</mrow>
                    </md>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>s-5\amp=-\sqrt{9}\cdot\sqrt{-1}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp s-5\amp=\sqrt{9}\cdot\sqrt{-1}</mrow>
                        <mrow>s-5\amp=-3i\amp\amp\text{or}\amp s-5\amp=3i</mrow>
                        <mrow>s\amp=5-3i\amp\amp\text{or}\amp s\amp=5+3i</mrow>
                    </md>
                The solution set is <m>\{5-3i, 5+3i\}.</m></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <!-- TODO: This one can be interactive -->
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve for <m>x</m> in <m>2x^2+12x+26=0</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We will use the completing-the-square method again. To do so, we first need to divide both sides by the leading coefficient, <m>2</m>.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>2x^2+12x\amp=-26</mrow>
                        <mrow>\divideunder{2x^2}{2}+\divideunder{12x}{2}\amp=\divideunder{-26}{2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>x^2+6x\amp=-13</mrow>
                        <intertext>Now we can add <m>\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^2=(3)^2=9</m> to both sides to complete the square.</intertext>
                        <mrow>x^2+6x\addright{9}\amp=-13\addright{9}</mrow>
                        <mrow>(x+3)^2\amp=-4</mrow>
                    </md>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>x+3\amp=-\sqrt{4}\cdot\sqrt{-1}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x+3\amp=\sqrt{4}\cdot\sqrt{-1}</mrow>
                        <mrow>x+3\amp=-2i\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x+3\amp=2i</mrow>
                        <mrow>x\amp=-3-2i\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=-3+2i</mrow>
                    </md>
                The solution set is <m>\{-3-2i, -3+2i\}.</m></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>The quadratic formula can also be used to solve for complex solutions. Here is an example where it makes more sense to use the quadratic formula.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve for <m>x</m> in <m>5x^2-2x=-3</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>If we were to complete the square, we would divide both sides by <m>5</m> and have lots of fractions in our equation. Instead, we will put the equation in standard form and use the quadratic formula.<md>
                    <mrow>5x^2-2x\amp=-3</mrow>
                    <mrow>5x^2-2x+3\amp=0</mrow>
                </md>We identify that <m>a=\substitute{5}</m>, <m>b=\substitute{-2}</m> and <m>c=\substitute{3}</m> and substitute them into the Quadratic Formula:<md>
                    <mrow>x\amp=\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{-(\substitute{-2})\pm\sqrt{(\substitute{-2})^2-4(\substitute{5})(\substitute{3})}}{2(\substitute{5})}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{2\pm\sqrt{4-60}}{10}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{2\pm\sqrt{-56}}{10}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{2\pm\sqrt{-1\cdot4\cdot14}}{10}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{2\pm\sqrt{-1}\cdot\sqrt{4}\cdot\sqrt{14}}{10}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{2\pm i\cdot2\cdot\sqrt{14}}{10}</mrow>
                </md>Now we need to put the solutions in standard form which is <m>a+bi</m>.<md>
                <mrow>x\amp=\frac{2}{10}\pm \frac{2i\sqrt{14}}{10}</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=\frac{1}{5}\pm \frac{\sqrt{14}}{5}i</mrow></md>
                The solution set is <m>\left\{\frac{1}{5}\pm \frac{\sqrt{14}}{5}i\right\}.</m></p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

